Michael&#39;s message from Monday, quoted below, covers an in-progress
change we would very much like feedback on from the library community,
and anyone with experience using Dublin Core elements/terms for
born-digital materials.

We feel confident we can insert the extra XML into the ARC file header
record, with negligible disruption to existing tools. Our questions are:
have we chosen the right initial set of fields, and the right syntax/naming
in both our use of DC and our own proposed namespace.

Any and all comments needed!

Thanks,

- Gordon @ IA

Michael Stack wrote:
&gt; This note is a follow on from a note sent a month ago by Gordon giving a 
&gt; heads-up and soliciting feedback on a new ARC file naming convention and 
&gt; of pending changes to the ARC file metadata record.
&gt; 
&gt; The change to the heritrix naming of ARCs has been completed and 
&gt; committed to the code base.  The format is now:
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;OPERATOR SPECIFIED&gt; &#39;-&#39; &lt;12 DIGIT TIMESTAMP&gt; &#39;-&#39; &lt;SERIAL NO.&gt; &#39;-&#39; &lt;FQDN 
&gt; HOSTNAME&gt; &#39;.arc&#39; | &#39;.gz&#39;
&gt; 
&gt; ... where &lt;OPERATOR SPECIFIED&gt; is any operator specified text, &lt;SERIAL 
&gt; NO&gt; is a zero-padded 5 digit number and &lt;FQDN HOSTNAME&gt; is the 
&gt; fully-qualified domainname on which the crawl was run.
&gt; 
&gt; Here is an example: UKGOV-200403221010-00004-debord.archive.org.arc.gz
&gt; 
&gt; The rest of this note is a more formal description of the HEADER section 
&gt; of Gordon&#39;s note describing the changes we intend to make to the ARC 
&gt; record metadata header and metadata body.  Again, comments are invited.
&gt; 
&gt; ARC FILE METADATA RECORD -- i.e. the first record of an ARC -- PROPOSED 
&gt; CHANGES
&gt; 
&gt; 1. If an ARC file metadata record has extra information in its body, the 
&gt; second &#39;&lt;reserved&gt;&#39; field of the second line of version 1 ARC files will 
&gt; be changed from &#39;0&#39; to &#39;1&#39;.  Previously, in version 1, ARC metadata 
&gt; records had zero-length bodies [See #1 for description of version 1 ARC 
&gt; files].
&gt; 2. If present, the ARC file metadata record body will contain at least 
&gt; the following fields.  Later revisions of may add other fields:
&gt; 
&gt; 2a.  Software and software version used creating the ARC file.  The 
&gt; value of this field is not overrideable by an operator.  Example: 
&gt; &#39;heritrix 0.7.1 http://crawler.archive.org&#39;.
&gt; 2b. The IP of the host that created the ARC file.  The value of this 
&gt; field is not overrideable by an operator.  Example: &#39;103.1.0.3&#39;.
&gt; 2c. The hostname of the host that created the ARC file.  The value of 
&gt; this field is not overrideable by an operator.  Example 
&gt; &#39;debord.archive.org&#39;.
&gt; 2d. Contact name of the crawl operator.   The operator will be able to 
&gt; set this value upon job creation.  Default value is &#39;admin&#39;. 2e. The 
&gt; http-header &#39;user-agent&#39; field from the crawl-job order file. This field 
&gt; is recorded here in the metadata only until the day ARCs record the HTTP 
&gt; request made.  Example: &#39;os-heritrix/0.7.0 (+http://localhost.localdomain)&#39;.
&gt; 2f. The http-header &#39;from&#39; from the crawl-job order file.  This field is 
&gt; recorded here in the metadata only until the day ARCs record the HTTP 
&gt; request made.  Example: &#39;webmaster@...&#39;.
&gt; 2g. The &#39;description&#39; from the crawl-job order file.  Example: &#39;Heritrix 
&gt; integrated selftest&#39;.
&gt; 2h. Robots obeyed.  Copied from crawl-job order file.  Example: &#39;true&#39;.
&gt; 2i. Organization on whose behalf the operator is running the crawl.  
&gt; Example &#39;Internet Archive&#39;.
&gt; 2j. The &#39;name&#39; from the crawl-job order file.  Example: &#39;Selftest&#39; or 
&gt; &#39;UKGOV-April2004&#39;.
&gt; 2k. The recipient of the crawl ARC resource if known.  Example: &#39;Library 
&gt; of Congress&#39;.
&gt; 
&gt; 3. The above listed fields will be written into the ARC file metadata 
&gt; body as validatable XML.
&gt; 4. The XML Schema used to validate will be in the main qualified Dublin 
&gt; Core [#2] with mixed in Internet Archive elements and refinements.  The 
&gt; DC elements with qualifiers will be used to describe the ARC resource 
&gt; itself.  The Internet Archive elements will be used to record 
&gt; information about the context in which the crawler wrote the ARC and 
&gt; Internet Archive element-qualifiers will be used refining DC elements.
&gt; 5.  Here are example XML instances to match the XML schema as yet 
&gt; undefined outlined in 4. above featuring the fields listed in 2. above.
&gt; 
&gt; 5.1 Selftest
&gt; 
&gt; Given:
&gt; 
&gt; Operator=&quot;stack at archive dot org&quot;
&gt; Organization=&quot;Internet Archive&quot;
&gt; Crawl-Job Description=&quot;Heritrix integrated selftest.&quot;
&gt; Crawl-Job Name=&quot;Selftest&quot;
&gt; Recipient of arc=&quot;Selftest analysis&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; The XML instance will look like:
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;arcmetadata xmlns=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:xsi=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance&quot;
&gt;  xsi:schemaLocation=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0 
&gt; http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/schema.xsd&quot;
&gt;  &lt;!--iac namespace done for sake of clarity demarking naming in the 
&gt; below.--&gt;
&gt;  xmlns:iac=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:dc=&quot;http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:dcterms=&quot;http://purl.org/dc/terms/&quot;&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;dc:publisher&gt;Internet Archive&lt;/dc:publisher&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:description&gt;Heritrix integrated selftest&lt;/dc:description&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:audience&gt;Selftest analysis&lt;/dcterms:audience&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:isPartOf xsi:type=&quot;dcterms:Collection&quot;&gt;Selftest&lt;/dcterms:isPartOf&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:operator&quot;&gt;stack at archive org&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:host-ip&quot;&gt;127.0.0.1&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:hostname&quot;&gt;localhost.localdomain&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:software&quot;&gt;Heritrix 0.7.1 
&gt; http://crawler.archive.org&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:robots-honored&gt;true&lt;/iac:robots-honored&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:http-header-from&gt;stack@...&lt;/iac:iac:http-header-from&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:http-header-user-agent&gt;os-heritrix/0.7.0 
&gt; (+http://localhost.localdomain)
&gt;     &lt;/iac:http-header-user-agent&gt;
&gt; &lt;!--Boilerplate--&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:type&gt;ARC file version 1.1&lt;/dc:type&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:conformsTo
&gt; xsi:type=&quot;dcterms:URI&quot;&gt;http://www.archive.org/web/researcher/ArcFileFormat.php&lt;/dcterms:conformsTo&gt;
&gt; &lt;/arcmetadata&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; 5.2 Library of Congress crawl run by Internet Archive
&gt; 
&gt; Given:
&gt; 
&gt; Operator=&quot;stack at archive dot org&quot;
&gt; Organization=&quot;Internet Archive&quot;
&gt; Crawl-Job Description=&quot;May 2004 Election Crawl.&quot;
&gt; Crawl-Job Name=&quot;Election2004-May&quot;
&gt; Recipient of arc=&quot;Library of Congress&quot;
&gt; 
&gt; The XML instance will look like:
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;arcmetadata xmlns=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:xsi=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance&quot;
&gt;  xsi:schemaLocation=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0 
&gt; http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/schema.xsd&quot;
&gt;  &lt;!--iac namespace done for sake of clarity demarking naming in the 
&gt; below.--&gt;
&gt;  xmlns:iac=&quot;http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:dc=&quot;http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/&quot;
&gt;  xmlns:dcterms=&quot;http://purl.org/dc/terms/&quot;&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; &lt;dc:publisher&gt;Internet Archive&lt;/dc:publisher&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:description&gt;May 2004 Election Crawl&lt;/dc:description&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:audience&gt;Library of Congress&lt;/dcterms:audience&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:isPartOf 
&gt; xsi:type=&quot;dcterms:Collection&quot;&gt;Election2004-May&lt;/dcterms:isPartOf&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:operator&quot;&gt;stack at archive org&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:host-ip&quot;&gt;123.1.2.3&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:hostname&quot;&gt;crawl08.archive.org&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:creator xsi:type=&quot;iac:software&quot;&gt;Heritrix 0.7.1 
&gt; http://crawler.archive.org&lt;/dc:creator&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:robots-honored&gt;false&lt;/iac:robots-honored&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:http-header-from&gt;stack@...&lt;/iac:iac:http-header-from&gt;
&gt; &lt;iac:http-header-user-agent&gt;os-heritrix/0.7.0 
&gt; (+http://localhost.localdomain)
&gt;     &lt;/iac:http-header-user-agent&gt;
&gt; &lt;!--Boilerplate--&gt;
&gt; &lt;dc:type&gt;ARC file version 1.1&lt;/dc:type&gt;
&gt; &lt;dcterms:conformsTo
&gt; xsi:type=&quot;dcterms:URI&quot;&gt;http://www.archive.org/web/researcher/ArcFileFormat.php&lt;/dcterms:conformsTo&gt;
&gt; &lt;/arcmetadata&gt;
&gt; 
&gt; 6. The IA schema of qualifiers and elements will be available at 
&gt; http://archive.org/arc/meta/1.0 (This URL is subject to change).  The DC 
&gt; schema is available at [#3].
&gt; 7. On the notion of adding the complete crawl-job order file to the ARC, 
&gt; that was made into an RFE at [#4].
&gt; 
&gt; #1. ARC file formal description: 
&gt; http://www.archive.org/web/researcher/ArcFileFormat.php.
&gt; #2. Dublic Core Metadata Initiative (DCMI): http://dublincore.org
&gt; #3. Notes on XML Schema for Qualified DC: 
&gt; http://dublincore.org/schemas/xmls/qdc/2003/04/02/notes/
&gt; #4. Adding crawl-job order file to arcs: 
&gt; http://sourceforge.net/tracker/index.php?func=detail&aid=955562&group_id=73833&atid=539102
&gt; 
&gt; Yours,
&gt; St.Ack
&gt; 
&gt; --- In archive-crawler@yahoogroups.com, &quot;Gordon Mohr (Internet Archive)&quot; 
&gt; &lt;gojomo@a...&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt; Thanks for the comments, everyone. Some of these are good ideas
&gt;  &gt; that we won&#39;t get to for 1.0, but will keep on the docket for
&gt;  &gt; later.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; kaisa_kaunonen wrote:
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Hi all,
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; good ideas you have, here are a couple of comments =&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; It&#39;s not possible to tell from file names which job each arc file
&gt;  &gt; &gt; comes from?
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Not automatically: it depends on the operator choosing an ARC name
&gt;  &gt; prefix that correlates with the Heritrix job name.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; I don&#39;t think we want to force these to be the same. The job
&gt;  &gt; names get a formulaic (timestamp) expansion for UI convenience
&gt;  &gt; and uniqueness within the application&#39;s domain. However, the
&gt;  &gt; naming needs for long-term ARC file archival may be different and
&gt;  &gt; thus can be chosen in separate ARC name options.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Job names should definitely go into the in-ARC header record;
&gt;  &gt; I&#39;ll make that a clear part of the arc-header spec.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; During harvesting every job has its own directory but in the end one
&gt;  &gt; &gt; may place all arcs into a bigger pool for further processing.
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Would a series number be unique only inside a job so you could have
&gt;  &gt; &gt; files
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp1 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp2 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; &gt; name - 00001-  timestamp3 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp4 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; produced by four different jobs. I somehow think a running series
&gt;  &gt; &gt; number in an archive implies that no two files in an archive have
&gt;  &gt; &gt; identical s-numbers (even if their timestamps differ)
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; The serial numbers are strictly within a single crawl/job for now.
&gt;  &gt; Attempting uniqueness over a larger domain would require other
&gt;  &gt; coordination between jobs, software runs, software installs, etc.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; It is currently up to the operator to vary the prefix-names on
&gt;  &gt; subsequent runs in such a situation. If they don&#39;t, the above
&gt;  &gt; is possible, which is a potential source of confusion with both
&gt;  &gt; the grouping you show, and when you consider that the default
&gt;  &gt; sort order of the ARCs of separate crawls will be...
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp1 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp3 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00001-  timestamp5 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00001 - timestamp7 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00002 - timestamp2 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00002 - timestamp4 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00002-  timestamp6 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; name - 00002 - timestamp8 - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Because of this, we&#39;ve decided to keep the timestamp and serial-number
&gt;  &gt; values in the current code&#39;s order, timestamp first, then serial-number,
&gt;  &gt; so that within a given &#39;name&#39;, the lexicographic sort order will always
&gt;  &gt; match the time-sort order.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; S-number makes file names more unique but it&#39;s not very informative.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; We find the serial numbers helpful as a way to highlight a
&gt;  &gt; particular ARC as the container of a resource of interest.
&gt;  &gt; For example, &quot;you can grep for the weird server response in ARC
&gt;  &gt; #27&quot;. The timestamps are somewhat more difficult to use as
&gt;  &gt; casual pointers.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Would it be possible to use job name instead
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; OperatorGivenName - Jobname - Timestamp - IP.arc.gz for example =&gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; finland - photoarchives - timestamp - IP.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; &gt;
&gt;  &gt; &gt; Slight problem of course that job names have variable lengths unlike
&gt;  &gt; &gt; s-numbers.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; I suspect many operators will want to make their ARC prefixes
&gt;  &gt; and jobnames match, but for the reasons listed above, I&#39;d
&gt;  &gt; rather not enforce that relationship in software.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Some other ideas for the future:
&gt;  &gt;   - an operator could be offered a easy way (checkbox?) to
&gt;  &gt;     make the ARC prefix conform to the job name
&gt;  &gt;   - an operator could be warned if a arc-prefix was used
&gt;  &gt;     in a known previous crawl, and offered a suggested
&gt;  &gt;     revision
&gt;  &gt;   - the crawler could consult an external inventory process
&gt;  &gt;     somewhere to verify that a proposed crawl name and
&gt;  &gt;     ARC prefix are unique
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Andrew Boyko wrote:
&gt;  &gt; # The ARC naming proposal sounds good to me.  The only thing I might
&gt;  &gt; # ponder is the idea of a separate identifier, for the instance of a
&gt;  &gt; # repeated crawl.   Obviously the operator could just add a suffix to the
&gt;  &gt; # &#39;operator-given-name&#39;, and the timestamp is a clear key to regularly
&gt;  &gt; # repeated crawls (monthly or weekly), so this isn&#39;t a big deal.  
&gt; Even so,
&gt;  &gt; # it&#39;s still compelling to have the tool auto-generate a sequence number
&gt;  &gt; # whenever a operator-given-name is reused within an instance of the 
&gt; tool.
&gt;  &gt; #  Two or three digits would presumably more than cover it.
&gt;  &gt; #
&gt;  &gt; # So in the example of repeated Congress crawls (to choose an example at
&gt;  &gt; # random :), assuming the same instance of the tool is used for each, the
&gt;  &gt; # seventh ARC for the fifth instance of the crawl would be
&gt;  &gt; #    CONGRESS005-00007-20040420133907-FG71E2B.arc.gz
&gt;  &gt; # where the 005 is automatically assigned by the crawler based on the
&gt;  &gt; # prior instances it knows of, and of course defaults to 001 for any new
&gt;  &gt; # crawl name.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; We&#39;ve been relying on operator diligence to do this, and picking 
&gt; date-related
&gt;  &gt; names -- things like CONGRESS0312 (dec 2003), CONGRESS0401 (jan 
&gt; 2004), etc.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; I agree automating this would be a big operator convenience For the 
&gt; current
&gt;  &gt; update, though, we&#39;ll leave this as a manual practice rather than rush in
&gt;  &gt; an automated system that might be constraining.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; # As far as the new header block, why not add the entire crawl order and
&gt;  &gt; # seed list?  A couple K added to a 100MB file shouldn&#39;t worry anyone.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Excellent point. It might also be achieved as a special record
&gt;  &gt; past the header; perhaps even as a crawler self-fetch, like...
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;    http://127.0.0.1:8080/currentcrawl/order.xml
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; It might be sufficient to do this only for the first ARC, or otherwise
&gt;  &gt; include this info by reference where preferred by the operator.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; - Gordon @ IA
